passages.text: Cambricon announced strong 2Q25 results (link), with 2025 revenues guidance at Rmb5bn to Rmb7bn, or midpoint at Rmb6bn (+411% YoY); our previous estimate of Rmb6.5bn is within the guidance range and 8% ahead of the midpoint guidance. We remain positive on Cambricon and raise our 12m TP by 14.7% to Rmb2,104 (implied 45x 2030E P/E) with 2030E EBITDA increased by 8% and 2030E target EV / EBITDA multiple increased by 6%. Our earnings raise is mainly on (1) higher AI chips shipment, reflecting rising China Cloud Capex in AI infrastructure investments, supportive government policies, and emergence of local chipsets in rising inferencing trend, and (2) enhancing opex ratio on rising revenues scale and improving operation efficiency. The company's revenues per engineer in the past 12 months increased to Rmb5m by June 2025 vs. Rmb2m by Dec 2024. Maintain Buy.

China Cloud Capex in expansion: BABA's 2Q25 capex beat at Rmb39bn (US\(5.4bn), up 57% QoQ or 2x YoY; Tencent's 2Q25 capex + 119% YoY, was better-than-feared, and GSe raised 2025E / 2026E capex by 23% / 17%, or 2026E Capex at +13% YoY (report link). Supportive AI policies: New guidelines were issued by the State Council (Link) which sets up a target of 70% + / 90% + of new-generation intelligent terminals and AI agents penetration rate by 2027 / 2030 in 6 key sectors (technology, industrial, consumer, welfare, governance, and global cooperation), highlighting actions plan to empower AI devices and improve efficiency. China AI supply chain delivered strong growth in 1H25, with Cambricon strong revenues growth, solid raw material (mainly wafer supply), and contract liabilities reflecting strong orders on hand; AI servers / Switch brands / ODMs sees rising China Cloud Capex, satisfied performance on inferencing powered by local chips, and rising local ecosystem (e.g. high-speed networking to unlock local chips performance, driving AI servers clusters scale up).

As we highlighted in early- 2025, we are positive on advanced nodes as generative AI development post local foundation models launched in late 2024 (e.g. DeepSeek) benefits China Semis development across IP, design, foundry, advanced packaging, and SPE. We upgraded SMIC to Buy in Feb, VeriSilicon and AMEC to Buy in Mar, and Cambricon to Buy in Apr with TP at Rmb1,223. Apart from China Semis, Huaqin (AP servers) Buy, added to CL list in Jun (link), we upgraded Inspur (AI servers) to Buy in Jul (link), initiated on Ruijie (Data center Switch) at Buy in Aug (link) and upgraded Sensetime (AI software) to Buy in Aug (link).

We expect Cambricon's continuous R&D investments in both Al chips (across training and inferencing) and Software (flexible and scalable coding system, allowing end users to easily develop algorithms of foundation models and related applications on its Al chips) could enhance its leading market position in local Al chips and expand its customers from software companies, enterprises (e.g. telcos, financial institutions) to more internet companies and China leading CSPs (cloud services providers).

We model Cambricon's Al chips shipment at 145k units in 2025E, to more than \(1m / 2m\) units in 2028E / 2030E. China Al chips market was at US \(19bn in 2024, and is expected to grow at +36% YoY in 2025 to US\) 26bn, and to grow at a +29% CAGR in 2025- 28 to US \(55bn, per IDC. We estimate Cambricon's Al chips to contribute US\) 912m / US \(6.1bn revenues in 2025E / 2028E, or 4\% / 11\%\) market share in China (vs. 1\% in 2024).

We continue to use a discounted EV/EBITDA to derive our 12m target price and continue to use 2030E as the base year, as EBITDA margins in 2030E (23%) are closer to global peers (NVIDIA / AMD at 66% / 26% in 2027E). We adopt a 69x EV / EBITDA multiple to 2030E EBITDA (vs. 65x previously) and discounted back to 2026E (no change) at 12.7% COE (no change). We continue to derive the EV / EBITDA multiple via peers' trading EV / EBITDA vs. forward year fundamentals (EBITDA YoY and EBITDA margin). The peers we use are China semi local leaders, and we use the average ratio of these peers' 2026E EV / EBITDA to 2027E EBITDA YoY and EBITDA margins to derive our target EV / EBITDA multiple for Cambricon. With 1.5x (no change, report link), and higher 2030E EBITDA YoY (24% vs. 23% previously) and 2030E EBITDA margin (23% vs. 22% previously), our target EV / EBITDA multiple is updated to 69x (vs. 65x previously). Our new 12- m target price is at Rmb2,104 (vs. Rmb1,835 previously). Maintain Buy.

2030E EV / Sales cross check: Our new TP of Rmb2,104 implies 10x 2030E EV / Sales (vs. 42% revenues YoY in 2030E), below the company's trading range since 2022 (22x- 61x EV / Sales), while within global peers' trading range: NVIDIA currently trades at 15x 2026E EV / Sales (vs. 26% revenues YoY in 2026- 27E on avg.), and AMD currently trades at 7x 2026E EV / Sales (vs. 16% revenues YoY in 2026- 27E on avg.), showing our valuation is not stretched.

2026E P/E cross check: Our new TP of Rmb2,104 implies 239x 2026E P/E (vs. 109% NI YoY and 26% OPM in 2027E), or 1.8x ratio, which is within China Semis peers, who enjoy above 30% NI YoY in 2027E, of 0.9x to 3.4x ratio, reflecting our valuation is not stretched.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
